TITLE: Plasma Physics 01: Plasma Orbital Theory.
	- Pre-requisitive: Electromagnetism 03.
	- Co-requisitive: Relativity 01.


Quick introductory understanding of plasma
	- What is Plasma?
		- Free charged carriers
		- No net charge
	- Fourth state of matter
		- Increasing temperature: Phase transitions
		- Ionization energy
			- Several substances/atoms
			- Example: Hydrogen energy levels.
			- Calc: Ionization energy of hydrogen.
			- Calc: Radiation wavelength bombardment to ionize.
		- Recall: Average energy per degree of freedom
		- Calc: Approximate temperature to become plasma
		- Ionization sources
	- Net Charge neutrality
		- Assume: Small sphere with charge inbalance inside plasma
		- Calc: Net charge of sphere
		- Calc: Potential from sphere to point outside it
		- Calc: Temperature required to balance electric potential
		- Note: Restoring forces appear to maintain electric neutrality
	- Debye–Hückel equation
		- Assume: Plasma potential (reference potential).
		- Assume: Plasma where the ith specie has charge qi and mean concentration ni_0.
		- Assume: Fixed volumetric charge density background where plasma is.
		- Calc: Potential energy of particles in plasma
		- Calc: Maxwell-Boltzmann distributon for charged carrier densities in the plasma.
		- Note: Non-linear PDE.
		- Calc: Approximation of high temperature plasma. Domain of validity.
		- Calc: Approximation to neutral plasma (no net charge).
		- Calc: The remaining poisson equation.
		- Def: The Debye–Hückel equation
		- Def: The Debye–Hückel length
		- Intuition: Background charge density is shielded by the plasma with the Debye–Hückel length.
	- Debye Shielding
		- Calc: Solution of poisson equation for background potential as ponctual charge (delta function).
		- Def: Debye Shielding length
		- Def: Debye Sphere. Volume of the Debye Sphere.
		- Example: Calc: Debye shielding length for hydrogen plasma at given temperature (say.. T=6000K).
		- Example: Calc: Debye shielding length for plasma of an element atomic number Z.
	- Plasma Frequency
		- Assume: External small displacement of entirety of given specie in an neutral plasma (plane symmetry)
		- Note: Sweeping away the plan catches more and more charges of this given specie.
		- Note: One side will remain negative, and the other positive (given the plasma is neutral).
		- Calc: Surface Charge density in the plane surface where the species were displaced.
		- Calc: Electric field formed by the displacement.
		- Calc: Apply newton's law to an individual displaced plasma particle of this specie (wanting to return!).
		- Note: Harmonic Oscilation Equation. Solution of the Equation of motion.
		- Def: Plasma (Angular) Frequency.
		- Def: Plasma Frequency.
		- Def: Plasma period.
		- Note: Oscilation happens due to electrostatic origins.
		- Note: Every different specie composing the plasma will have a different oscilation frequency.
		- Def: Electron Plasma Frequency (Note: Fast oscilation).
		- Def: Ion Plasma Frequency (Note: Slow oscilation).
	- Criterions of plasma definition
		- Dimensions is much greater than debye shielding length.
		- Number of electrons is debye sphere be large
		- Net Neutrality
		- Collision frequency much smaller than plasma frequency (st oscilation is observed).
		- Question: What happens if each criterion is not met?
	- Examples of Plasma
		- Solar Wind. Park/Archimidean spirals.
		- Van-Alley Radiation belts. Magnetosphere.
		- Ionosphere.
	- Aplications
		- Pinch machines. Nuclear Fusion.
		- MHD Generator. MHD Pumps. MHD Drive (on submarines..).
		- Plasma Propulsion.
		- Solid State Plasmas (Free electrons and holes) (Quantum).



