Particula carregada em campo magnético não-uniforme
	- Average force over gyration period
		- Assumption: Particle moves due to Zero-Order term only.
			- First-order forces does not causes particle to move
			- In reality: Small shift in orbit due to first-order term
		- First order force
			- Calc: First-order term of force of particle
			- Calc: Partial derivative of magnetic field in r. (cylindrical).
			- Calc: First-order term of force of particle in cylindrical coordinates
			- Note: Field lines not curved ==> We can shift reference frame to go with particle
			- Assume: Shift frame to move with particle (v parallel).
			- Note: Now direction r has only x, y components.
			- Calc: First order force in this reference frame
		- The velocity
			- Velocity in cylindrical coordinates
			- If charge carrier has positive charge
			- If charge carrier has negative charge
			- Calc: First order force components (k and r).
		- Parallel and perpendicular contribution
			- Calc: Parallel contribution of first-order force
			- Calc: Perpendicular contribution of first-order force.
			- Calc: Parallel/Perpendicular contributions using magnetic moment.
		- Calc: Average Parallel/Perpendicular contributions over gyration period
		- Note: We shall ignore the orbit itself, and look to the guiding center.
	- The parallel force
		- Show: Divergence of B-Field in cylindrical coordinates (its zero!).
		- Show: Br/r is approximately equal to dBr/dr
		- Calc: Average over gyration period of each term of the divergence.
		- Calc: The dBr/dr term in function of dBz/dz term.
		- Note: Bz is approximately B (since there are small variations).
		- Calc: Averaged parallel contribution using magnetic moment.
		- Note: Parallel components of gradient of |B| contributes with the parallel average.
	- The perpendicular force
		- Calc: Circunferencial path in cylindrical coordinaes
		- Calc: Calculation of the average of perpendicular term
		- Note: Average of square sin/cos is 1/2. Other terms are zero.
		- Note: Bz is approximately B (since there are small variations).
		- Calc: Averaged perpendicular contribution
		- Note: Perpendicular components of gradient of |B| controbites with perpendicular average.
	- The total force
		- Calc: Força total média (Contribuição perpendicular e paralela)
		- Use: Identidade vetorial: (d x B) x B = (B * d)B - d(1/2 B^2).
		- Calc: Força total média
		- Calc: Força total média usando moento magnético vetorial.
		- Note: First term is the force acting on magnetic dipole.
	- Current drift and velocity drift
		- Remmember: Drift velocity of a general external force
		- Note: Parallel contribution will cause no drift. Only perpendicular one.
		- Calc: Drift veolcity of the perpendicular force
		- Note: Drift velocity depends on charge ==> There will be current
		- Calc: Drift current density caused by perpendicular forc
	- Adiabatic invariant from parallel acceleration
		- Def: Adiabatic invariant: Stays constant under slow change.
		- Note: Parallel force will cause parallel acceleration
		- Calc: Multiply by v_parallel and identify energy.
		- Calc: Flip to perpendicualr work by conservation of energy
		- Calc: Derivative of magnetic moment (using d/dt(Wt B/B)).
	- First Adiabatic Invariant
		- The MAgnetic moment
		- Calc: Magnetic flux over gyration orbit
		- Note: Depends on the magnetic moment
		- Note: Magnetic flux over gyration orbit is also an adiabatic invariant
	- Magnetic Mirror Effect
		- Particle will decrease parallel velocity under magnetic field convergence
		- Note: Particle might be reflected back by magnetic field convergence
		- Application: Trapping plasma particles
		- Calc: Pitch angle limitations using first adiabatic invariant
		- Calc: Minimum pitch angle for reflection
		- Def: Mirror ratio
		- Cone loss in magnetic mirrors
	- Curvature Drift
		- Consider: Non-linear coordinate system along magnetic field line
		- Triedro de Fresnel: Tangent, Normal, Torsion.
		- Calc: Centripetal force in direction normal to magnetic field line.
		- Differential along tangent of magnetic field line (its the d-angle).
		- Calc: dB/ds (tangent / arc line). Also: d/ds = B * nabla.
		- Calc: Centripetal force using tangent versor
		- Calc: Centripetal force using magnetic field itself
		- Calc: Curvature drift caused by centripetal force
		- Calc: Current drift caused by centripetal force
	- Gradient-Curvature drift
		- Gradient drift
		- Curvature drift
	- Example: Van Alley Radiation Belts
		- Particle bounds back and forth between magnetic mirrors (Earth poles)
		- Westward drift current of charged particles
		- Ring Current.


